Discussion In order to demonstrate the utility of our screen, we generated mutant DhlAs. The DhlA gene was cloned and transformed into a mutator strain and the transformants were allowed to grow for 40 generations. Mutant DNA under the control of Ptac was then electroporated into competent E. coli. Transformants were selected on LB agar containing ampicillin. Following growth, the transformants were replicated using nitrocellulose membranes onto LB plates containing the pH indicator, bromothymol blue. Within 3±5 h, the colonies became blue. At that time, the ®lters were transferred to fresh plates containing IPTG and volatile halogenated organic was added in the lid of each Petri dish. After the addition of substrate, protons released by dehalogenase activity caused the bromothymol blue color to change to yellow. The rate of the blue to yellow transition was used as an indicator of the amount of activity. The indicator plates provided a simple means with which to identify mutant dehalogenases with increased activity










