and/or altered substrate speci®city. Dierent volatile halogenated alkanes may be employed to determine the breadth of speci®city. We used these plates to screen approximately 50,000 mutants and identi®ed one mutant with apparently improved dehalogenation activity when 1,2-dichloroethane was the substrate. Sequencing of this mutant revealed a change at A149. Based on our results with the indicator plates, we selected and further characterized the A149T mutant. We have also developed a DhlA activity assay in whole cells. This assay employs a suspension of cells that have been induced to express DhlA. These cells were suspended in a weakly buered solution, the absorbance at 600 nm was determined and then pH indicator and cells were mixed and exposed to DCA. Cell suspension without DCA was used as a negative control. Following incubation, the cells were removed by centrifugation








and the rate of change in absorbance at 615 nm was used to determine the relative DhlA activity. The utility of this assay is supported by its qualitative agreement with in vitro kinetic studies using puri®ed enzymes. The in vivo assay showed slightly greater than twofold increase in activity for the A149T mutant (Fig. 3). The kcat value for the A149T mutant was approximately 1.5fold greater than the wild type (Table 2). We noticed that the best results can be achieved by measuring the absorbance at 615 nm soon after visual observation of the pH indicator color change, and by employing chemical inhibitors to terminate the DhlA reaction. This assay can be easily modi®ed into a microtiter plate format for high-throughput screening of DhlA mutants. Though a similar application utilizing 96-well plates has been reported,26 our procedure bypasses the lysis step, thereby signi®cantly reducing both the time and reagent quantities required for the screening. The A149T enzyme was puri®ed and its activity was compared with that of the wild type enzyme. The A149T mutant displayed a modest (1.3±1.6 fold) increase in kcat at all pHs. The Km for 1,2-dichloroethane was similar to wild type at low pHs, but was increased 10-fold at pH 8.2, the wild type enzyme's pH optimum. This increase of Km in the A149T mutant is probably due to the high level of 1,2-dichloroethane used in the screen, and makes this mutant less suitable for application at this pH. Although the fastest turnover occurred at pH 8.2 for the A149T mutant, the 10-fold lower Km at pH 7.2 results in the highest speci®city constant (kcat/Km) at pH 7.2 (Table 2). The optimal speci®city constant has shifted from pH 8.2 in the wild type (647,000 MÀ1 sÀ1) to pH 7.2 in the mutant (330,000 MÀ1 sÀ1). Since the speci®city constant (kcat/Km) represents a rate constant at very low concentrations of substrate, the pH optimum of the mutant enzyme is 7.2.





